problem:
Let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
\sqrt{x} &\text{ if }x>4, \\
x^2 &\text{ if }x \le 4.
\end{array}
\right.\]Find $f(f(f(2)))$.

solution:
Simplifying, we have: \begin{align*}
2a(2a^2 + a) - a^2 &= 2a(2a^2) + 2a(a) - a^2 \\
&= 4a^3 + 2a^2 - a^2 = \boxed{4a^3 + a^2}.
\end{align*}

Cross multiplying, we obtain $ x+1 = 2(3x-1)$. (This is the same thing as multiplying both sides by both $3x-1$ and by $x+1$.)  Then, we solve for $x$: \begin{align*}
x+1 &= 2(3x-1)\\
\Rightarrow \qquad x+1 &= 6x-2\\
\Rightarrow \qquad-5x &= -3\\
\Rightarrow \qquad x &= \boxed{\frac{3}{5}}.
\end{align*}

When using the distributive property for the first time, we add the product of $x+3$ and $x$ to the product of $x+3$ and $-8$:

\begin{align*}
(x+3)(x-8) &= (x+5) \cdot x + (x+5) \cdot (-8)\\
&= x(x+3) - 8(x+3)
\end{align*}We use the distributive property again and combine like terms:

\begin{align*}
x(x+3) - 8(x+3) &= x^2 + 3x - 8x - 24\\
&= \boxed{x^2 - 5x - 24}
\end{align*}

We apply the order of operations.  To see that this means to sum the denominator first, note that we can write the expression as \[1 + 2/\left(3 + \frac{4}{5}\right).\] So, we have \begin{align*}
1 + \frac{2}{3+\frac{4}{5}} &= 1 + \frac{2}{\frac{15}{5} + \frac{4}{5}}\\
&= 1 + \frac{2}{\frac{19}{5}} \\
&= 1 + 2\cdot\frac{5}{19} =1 + \frac{10}{19}=\frac{19}{19} + \frac{10}{19} = \boxed{\frac{29}{19}}.
\end{align*}

